Cartarch — Alembic migration environment (introduced in the Gate #4 baseline).

Single-database config. The DB URL is env-driven via DATABASE_URL (the same seam
as app/db.py): unset → the app's SQLite file; set → Postgres
(postgresql+psycopg://...). env.py points target_metadata at app's Base.metadata
and also imports app/legacy_tables.py so autogenerate sees the 7 raw-SQL tables.

================================================================================
SCHEMA OWNERSHIP (post Gate #4)
================================================================================
The legacy scripts/run_migrations.py self-migration runner is RETIRED — the app
no longer creates or migrates schema at boot. Schema is owned by Alembic:

  Fresh database (CI, disaster recovery, an empty sandbox), in order:
      alembic upgrade head            # creates all 28 tables (21 ORM + 7 raw)
      python scripts/seed_reference_data.py   # idempotent reference-data seed

  At deploy this runs as a single PRE-SYNC JOB, not per-pod. The app pods boot
  AFTER it; booting against a never-migrated DB leaves the 7 raw tables missing
  (init_db()'s create_all only builds the 21 ORM tables — see app/main.py).

The per-version scripts/migrate_v3_*.py + run_migrations.py + app/migrations.py
are DEAD post-baseline and kept on disk only as history (unwired — nothing
imports the runner). EXCEPTION: the 3 seed scripts
(migrate_v3_15_0_seed_{bracket_rules,game_changers,card_tags}.py) are still LIVE
— scripts/seed_reference_data.py imports them.

The schema_migrations ledger table is orphaned at runtime (only the retired
runner machinery ever read it) and is NOT part of the baseline. Leave it in the
existing SQLite DB (harmless, unread; that DB is replaced at cutover). At the
Postgres cutover, pgloader must EXCLUDE schema_migrations — the PG baseline schema
has no such table.

================================================================================
POSTGRES CUTOVER — `alembic stamp head` (DOCUMENTATION ONLY — DO NOT RUN NOW)
================================================================================
This is the cutover-time procedure (gate #8 rehearsal / the real cutover). It is
recorded here for reference; nothing in this gate executes it.

The migrated Postgres database arrives with its DDL ALREADY matching the baseline
and its data ALREADY loaded by pgloader. You therefore STAMP, never upgrade:

  1. Create the empty baseline schema on the target PG with the PG-correct types
     (native boolean, naive timestamp, SERIAL PKs, FK ondelete, partial uniques):
         alembic upgrade head        # against the empty target PG
  2. pgloader copies prod DATA into that schema (data-only; schema already exists).
     pgloader config must: NO global boolean→integer cast (would break
     game_changer_cards.active WHERE active), EXCLUDE schema_migrations, and reset
     sequences via setval after load.
  3. The DDL now matches the baseline and data is present, so mark the baseline as
     applied WITHOUT re-running it:
         alembic stamp head
     (Step 1's `upgrade head` already wrote alembic_version; `stamp head` is the
     operation to use if instead the schema was created by some other means — e.g.
     pgloader-created — so Alembic records the baseline as applied without trying
     to CREATE already-existing tables. Use exactly one of upgrade-then-load or
     load-into-stamped; never `upgrade head` against a schema that already exists.)

After cutover, `alembic upgrade head` applies only revisions AFTER the baseline.
Run scripts/seed_reference_data.py is NOT needed at cutover (pgloader brought the
seed rows); it is idempotent if run anyway.
